2 - Intro To LAN

What is a topology?

It’s how devices are connected inside a network so they can send data to each other. Usually this involves switches, hubs, and cables, but the structure differs depending on the topology.

- Star Topology

A switch or hub sits in the middle, and all devices connect to it.

Good way of organizing a network
Easy to manage and troubleshoot because each device is separate
If one device fails, the rest still works

- Bus Topology

A main backbone cable, and devices connect to it.

Data is sent through the main cable to all devices
Only the correct device accepts the data
If something happens to the main cable, the whole network goes down

- Ring Topology

Devices are connected in a loop (ring), and data travels through each device until it reaches the intended one.

No central switch or hub
Data flows in one direction
Each device passes the data along
If a device wants to send its own data, it sends it into the ring
If one device or connection breaks, it can affect the whole network

. Switches

This is a very interesting topic and I want to learn more about it.

A switch is a dedicated device inside a network that allows devices like PCs, printers, and phones to connect.

But more importantly:

It sends data to the correct device using MAC addresses

It doesn’t just connect devices, it actually decides where data should go

